he editors of the leading\npapers and explain its objections\nand that the Nisei vets and all others\ndo likewise in writing.\nThe idea. is noble. indeed. but the\ncopyreaders won't like it.\nIf the word \"Jap\" is put out of\nuse. the copyreadors will find it\nquite difficult to write 24 or 36-\npoint one-column headlines. After\nall. \u201cJap\u201d is a three-letter word\nand \u201cJapanese\" contains eight let\nters.\nBut if the editors and publishers\nagree to discard the word. \"Jap\".\nmay God help the copyreaders who\u2018\nhandle Far East copy.\n0 D I\nQ PURELY\npersonal piffles more and\nmore. Niseiviile is taking on a pre\nwar color what the calendar being\nfilled months in advance with pic\nnics. bazaars and dances \u201chard\ntimes\u201d. depression. recession or what\nover you want to call it. is ap\nproaching but big cities like Chi\nman and New York are likely to\nfeel it before we do the local\nJACL has installed its officers so\nthe m in Seattle and vicinity\nW \u201cthe m d an office\nto M m shims any\nany W Celebra-\nMasada [leads for Midwest Session;\nAlso Books Jaunt to Tennessee\nWASHINGTON. D. 0.. June 35\nMike Masaoh. mm um. ADC}\n1% mm. Mt My to\nI\u201c the \u201cannual meeting of\n.0 mm W Council But\nsud \u201dby In Guano.\nm m \u201ck at the council\n_t?) may Sunday\nf U nr. 'Mlph M. Sa\nh\ufb02. \u201dI\nw d b \u201cwas! District\nd Ch\nM u \u201dhi m a lease\n\u201dMing Your \u00abWNW!\nSPECIAL REPRESENTATIVES\nWAI\u2019ATO\u2014Mrs. Kara Kondo\nP. 0. Box 816, Wapato, Wash.\nONTARIO\u2014Mrs. James Wannabe\nRt. 1. Fayette. ldsho\nI SPOKANE\u2014chhc Shlouk!\nBox 6058. Spokane 14, Wash.\nBus. 61.. 1548 Rel. GL. 7197\nJust among People\nby gordon lzirabayashi\nable to pay. the cost will be spread\nout and paid by all workers and\ntheir employers at a time when the\nworkers are earning wages and best\nIble to afford it.\"\nSome writers argue that it is \u201cnot\nthe American way.\u201d What can he\nsaid about that powerful accusa\ntion? Well. we used to have only\nprivate schools for those who could\npay for it. Now, the chief burden\nof education falls on the state and\neducational opportunities are open\nto all. There are people who think\nthis to be more democratic. more\nthe \"American way.\" Instead of just\nprivate property. we have national.\u2018\nstate. and city parks available to?\nall citizens.\nWe have the post office. the social\n\u2018security. the public highways. Every\nfair-sized incorporated community\nhas a police and fire departments.\npublicly supported for all concerned.\n\u2018ls not health of sufficient impor\n.tance to the community to meet it\n'pubncly, too?\ntion\" next summer will be a boon\nto the merchants here as its com.\nmittee workers hope to entice much\noutside trade in an effort to intro\nduce the cosmopolitan atmosphere\nof this area memo to D. 0.:\nwhat was once Japanese town is\nnow very much Bronzeviile (Jackson\nSt. from Fifth to Twali\u2018th)\nauto salesman Frank Nagamine is\npicking up where he left off at the\ntime of evacuation and he is doing\nwell. we hear a sign that most\nof the men already have been dis\npatched to Alaska salmon canneries:\nFilipiims are becoming scarce on\nthe corner of Third and Main\n0 I O\nQ AFTER\nreading between the lines on the\nwedding of Marilyn Paula Green\nberg to Paul Robeson. Jr.. in New\nYork last Sunday. one would jump\nto the conclusion that it is a horri\nble. unimaginable crime for a white\ngirl to marry a Negro.\nSociety's attitude toward the inter\nmarriage was reilected in the AP\nreport:\u201cSome in the crowd booed as\nthe wedding party left the building.\"\nAnd the tone of the press re\nlenses did not improve when Singer\nPaul Robeson. the father of the\nyoung groom. burst out with. \u201cThis\nmarriage would not have caused any\nexcitement in the Soviet Union.\"\nAs far as we are concerned. the\nmarriage is the couple\u2018s own pri\nvate business\u2014definitely, not ours\nThe rugged barriers which they are\nsure to face are their business. too.\n\u2014bf\nm: attending will include:\n\u201cI\u201c. Cleveland. Cincinnati.\nI Louis. Detroit. the newest chap\nIn the council. Dayton. Ohio. and\n\"I! hd \u201cpter.\nGI July 1. Masaoka will leave for\nNashville. Tenn. for a meeting of\nthe Race Relations Board of the\n\u2019American Missionary Association at\nIF\u2018islte University. He will act as\nconsultant for several sessions at\nthe race relations institution con\nducted by the association.\niii\u201c- \u201cGREAT WISDOM\"\n5 By GmRGE 3. BENSON Ere 9\nP 1 d G Harding Collage\nw \u201cI 9.3117. Ariana M\nThe other day a friend of mine\nsent me a copy ol a quotation. say\ning that he was putting a copy of\nsame into his scrapbOOk. He copied\nit from a Canadian publication un\nder the title: \u201cGreat Wisdom.\" The.\nwhole thing is so well put, and car-l\nries such good old fashioned logic.\u2018\nthat I thought you might like to\u2018\nhave it. too. The message of the\nwhole piece packs a genuine waliop.\nI'll let you have it. as follows:\n\u201cThere are a few great documents.\nwhich cmtain so much wisdom that\nthey can bear endless repeating.\nHere is an example: \u2018I place economy\namong the first and most impor-\u2018\n'ant virtues. and public debt as the\ngreatest of dangers to be feared. To\npreserve our independence, We must\nnot let our rulers load us with per\nnetuai debt.\nRigid Economy\n\u2018We must make our choice be\ntween economy and liberty. or pro\nfusion and servitude. If we run\ninto such debts. we must be taxed\nin our meat and drink. in our ne\ncessities and in our comforts. in our\nlabors and in our amusements. I!\nwe can prevent the government\nfrom wasting the labors of the peo\nnle under the pretense of caring\nfor them. they will be happy.\n\u201c\u2018The same prudence which in\nnrivate life would forbid our paying\nmoney for unexplained projeas.\nforbids it in the disposition of pub\u2014\u2018\nlic money. We are endeavoring to\nreduce the government to the prac\n'ice of rigid economy to avoid bur\nclening the people and arming the\nMagistrate with a patronage of mo\nney which might be used to corrupt\n'he principles of our government.\u2019\nNo Reactionary\n\"The man who wrote this was\nnot some reactionary believer in an\nold system of society. He was no\nenemy of the masses of the workers.\nHe was not a great capitalist. trying\nto maintain special privilege, nor\nwas he the heir ol\u2019 a great fortune\n'rying to preserve it. He was the\nfirst of the great democrats of\nNorth America. a man whose name\nis commemorated and revered by\nall believers in human liberty.\n\"His is a name permanently\nlinked in history with the struggle\nagainst oppression. The words were\nwritten by Thomas Jefferson.\"\nThere _vou have it in full force. The\n60 cents\nJACKSON\nGROCERY\n1303 Jackson St. El. 0008\nProp. Mrs. lhnmh Muhwn\nGyokko-Ken\nGale\n308-510 Main St.\nMA. 3662\nSeattle 4, Wash.\nShoes for the entire family.\ni a \u201935::\nI\ni 3\u201c\u201c News 4W\ngar; p 0\n\u2018l\u2018 ge\"\n1 \u00a359 \ufb01\u2018\ufb01\ufb01k\u201c\n3,. \u2018u N\nWEN\u201c \u201ca\u201c?\nO\u2018Cy\ufb01s\ufb01j\ufb01\na'\ufb01Q W... k\u201c f s\nriff. N. M\nm MI.\na\u201c [-101\nUrakawa\u2019s\nTOKTOW SHOE STORE\n826 Jackson St. SEneca. 707 a\nSeattle, Wash.\nStore hours: 9 am. to 7 p.m., week days.\n9 am. to 9 p.m., Saturdays.\nH \"3 \u201c:3.\" 334\u201d\u201c \u201c2.x \u201d5...\u201d\nTHE NORTHWEST TIMES\nimpact of this Jeffersonian wisdom\nis greatly needed today. Crisis is\nbefore us in these times. in an even\nmore serious way than in Jefferson\u2019s\ntime.\nPractice Economy\nNowadays. nobody pays much at\ntention to the national debt. on.\nwe think. it's just some big figure\nthat, the statisticians use. Besides.\nWhy bother about it, don\u2018t we owe\nit to ourselves? Jefferson has given\nus the answers. We owe it to our\nselves all right. that is it. We owe\nit to ourselves to get our whole gov\nernmental budget in a stable and\nbalanced condition. Our $250 billion\nnational debt represents obligations\nof the government to the people.\nWith more deficit spending and\npublic borrowing, this debt would\ngrow. Our Whole national financial\nstructure would become more un\nhealthy and unstable. Interest pay\nments are already fantastic. with\nnot much attempt in proposed bud\ngets to Whittle down the principal.\nWe cannot afford higher taxes. We\nmust not be so foolish as to indulge\nin deficit spending. The only way\nout is to get our fiscal house in order\nby following the advice laid down\nby Thomas Jefferson: practice eco\nnomy. The report of the Hoover\nCommission explains how we could\nsave between three and five billion\ndollars a year without impairing\ngovernment services and without any\nwholesale firing of employees. Will\nwe insist that our government follow\nthe plan?\nHomes For Sale\nBEACON HILL BRICK\nFour bedrooms. Living room\nwith fireplace. dining room. kit\nchen with nook, hardwood floors.\nVenetian blinds throughout. Full\nbasement, new furnace. Detached\ngarsge. This house to close to Be:-\ncon mu school. shopping center\nand bus. Sellln; at G. I. appraise]\n$11,500.\nBEACON HILL CORNER\nModern. seven years old. Two\nbedrooms. Living room with fire\nplace, dining room, attractive kit\nchen. Basement with oil furnace\nand air conditioner. Hardwood\nfloors. Additionui space upstairs\nfor third bedroom. Well land\nscaped. Asking $9.500. Terms.\n0o e\nInte '0\nmat! nal\nRealty\nJames M. Matsuoiu\n659 Jackson St. MA. 1522\nScuttle 4, Wash.\nMain\ni \ufb02asks}:\nNisei Prepsters\nPicked Officers\nSeveral girls have been chosen\nofficers for the coming year at their\nschools.\nAt Garfiel\u00a2 Yone Kanda is presi\ndent of the \u201c0\" Club with Tomi\nYoshloka and Dorothy Iwasaki alw\nin the cabinet. Lily Endo is the first\nvice president of the Girls' Club.\nAlso in the cabinet are Marianne\nOtoshi, June Watch-be and Jane\nOkamoto.\nTomi Fujino is pres